    "summary": "The Ajanta Caves (c. 2nd century BC–5th century AD) are a complex of 30 rock-cut Buddhist cave temples in Maharashtra, India, whose paintings and sculptures represent the pinnacle of ancient Indian classical art. The caves were excavated in two phases: an earlier Hinayana phase (2nd–1st century BC) and a later Mahayana phase under Gupta-era patronage (5th century AD), with the latter producing the most celebrated paintings. The murals depict Jataka tales (stories of the Buddha's previous lives), the life of the Buddha, and scenes of court life and nature in vivid detail, with elegant figural compositions and sophisticated use of color, shading, and foreshortening.\n\nThe Ajanta paintings are significant both as art and as historical documents — they show costumes, jewelry, musical instruments, architecture, and daily life from ancient India with a richness of detail found nowhere else. The caves were abandoned and forgotten sometime around the 7th century, becoming entirely overgrown by jungle, until a British officer stumbled upon them while hunting in 1819. The murals had been preserved by the dry, sheltered conditions inside the caves — paradoxically, their abandonment protected them. The Ajanta paintings influenced Buddhist art across Asia, with copies and adaptations appearing in Sri Lanka, Central Asia, and East Asia. Today recognized as a UNESCO World Heritage Site, they remain among the finest examples of pre-modern world art.",
